<br>
The guy who left the baby in the car to cook to death clearly was culpable.<br>
<br>
But whereas God is supposed to have all this supernatural power, and is often claimed to &quot;intervene&quot; miraculously in, e.g., life-threatening disease, what culpability does God have in the case provided? Heck, did God even need to do anything more than tweak some bystander's brain to be curious, wander by the car, and perhaps peek inside?<br>
<br>
Or do people claim it is &quot;God's plan&quot; that the young-un died in such manner that it did? And if so, as an aside, just what do you expect that baby's afterlife will be like in heaven, not having lived &quot;a full life&quot; here on earth?<br>
<br>
-Rusty <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=notemilydickinson>Not Emily Dickinson</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 21<br> <font color=#3333ff>(3/10/03 3:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=149.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Culpability</span><hr size=1> I took a philosophy of religion course in college that explored the philosophical arguments for and against the existance of god.  One of the standard argument against the existence of god is that if god is omnipotent, omniscient, and omnibenevolent, evil would not exist in this world.  The comeback from the &quot;God Does Exist&quot; camp is that humans have been given free will.<br>
<br>
I am sure that people will say that it is part of God's plan for this child to die because he gave humans free will.  <br>
<br>
I am interested in reading the responses about the afterlife of the baby.  <br>
<br>
What if the baby had not been baptized???<br>
<br>
<br>
